Desert Ecology

For this assignment, we are going to use a modified data set on desert ecology. The data are from: S. K. Morgan Ernest, Thomas J. Valone, and James H. Brown. 2009. Long-term monitoring and experimental manipulation of a Chihuahuan Desert ecosystem near Portal, Arizona, USA. Ecology 90:1708.

This data is tidy because each variable has its own column, each observation has its own row, and each value has its own cell.

deserts %>%

  1. What is the range of weight for each species included in the study? Remove any observations of weight that are NA so they do not show up in the plot.
deserts %>% 
  filter(weight!="NA") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=species, y=weight))+
  geom_boxplot()+
  scale_y_log10()+
  coord_flip()

  1. Add another layer to your answer from #5 using geom_point to get an idea of how many measurements were taken for each species.
deserts %>% 
  filter(weight!="NA") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=species, y=weight))+
  geom_boxplot()+
  geom_point(size=0.5)+
  scale_y_log10()+
  coord_flip()

  1. Dipodomys merriami is the most frequently sampled animal in the study. How have the number of observations of this species changed over the years included in the study?
view(deserts)
deserts %>% 
  filter(species=="merriami") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=year))+
  geom_bar()+
  labs(title = "Dipodomys merriami Count over the Years")+
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size=rel(1.5), hjust = 0.5))

  1. What is the relationship between weight and hindfoot length? Consider whether or not over plotting is an issue.
deserts %>% 
  filter(weight!="NA") %>% 
  filter(hindfoot_length!="NA") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=weight, y=hindfoot_length))+
  geom_point(size=0.05, color="blue")+
  geom_smooth(method = lm)+
  labs(title = "Weight vs. Hindfoot",
       x = "Weight",
       y = "Hindfoot Length")+
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 14, face = "bold", hjust = 0.5),
        axis.text = element_text(size = 8),
        axis.title = element_text(size = 10))
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

Over-plotting does seem to be an issue in this case, because even with very small points it is hard to separate points on the plot.

  1. Which two species have, on average, the highest weight? Once you have identified them, make a new column that is a ratio of weight to hindfoot_length. Make a plot that shows the range of this new ratio and fill by sex.
deserts %>% 
  filter(species_id!="NA"| species_id!="DS") %>% 
  filter(weight!="NA" & hindfoot_length!="NA" & sex!="NA") %>% 
  mutate(ratio=weight/hindfoot_length) %>% 
  select(species_id, sex, weight, hindfoot_length, ratio) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=species_id, y=ratio, fill=sex))+
  geom_boxplot()+
  labs(title = "Range of Weight/Hindfoot Length for Species NL and DS",
       x = "Species ID",
       y = "Weight/Hindfoot Length")+
  scale_y_log10()
